$lang['The hexadecimal, or base-16, system was designed to emulate some of the same properties as the decimal system. In other words, it was created to make things easier for us humans. The number 423 has 16 digits instead of 10 digits available in a decimal system. This is because hexadecimal uses a base of 16 symbols instead of 10. After F, the order begins again with 0 and so on and so forth until we get to 15 which is notated as F.'] = 'I hoahoatia te punaha hexadecimal, turanga-16 ranei, ki te whai i etahi o nga ahuatanga rite ki te punaha ira. Arā, he mea hanga hei whakangāwari ake i a tātou te tangata. Ko te nama 423 he 16 mati hei utu mo te 10 mati kei roto i te punaha ira. Ko tenei na te mea hexadecimal e whakamahi ana i te turanga o nga tohu 16 hei utu mo te 10. I muri i te F, ka timata ano te ota ki te 0, ka pera tonu me etahi atu tae noa ki te 15 kua tohua ko F.';
$lang['Hexadecimal encoding reduces the number of digits by a factor of eight when compared to the decimal system. Additionally, hexadecimal numbers have an information density that is twice as high as decimal numbers do. So, why should you bother learning this funky little numbering scheme? Because it can make your life easier! When working with digital systems or data transmission, using hex will save you time and energy when decoding cryptic messages or data streams.'] = 'Ko te whakawaehere hautekauono ka whakaiti i te maha o nga mati ma te tauwehe waru ina whakaritea ki te punaha ira. I tua atu, ko nga tau hautekauono he kiato korero e rua te teitei ake i nga tau ira. Na, he aha koe ka raru ai ki te ako i tenei kaupapa nama iti rorirori? Na te mea ka ngawari ake to oranga! I te wa e mahi ana me nga punaha matihiko, te tuku raraunga ranei, ma te whakamahi hex ka whakaora koe i te wa me te kaha ki te wetewete i nga karere ngaro, i nga awa raraunga ranei.';
